DOCUMENT();

#image scale
$imgScale = .2;

#image aspect ratio
$width = $imgScale*1609;
$height = $imgScale*1287;

loadMacros(   
	"PGstandard.pl",     # Standard macros for PG language
	"MathObjects.pl",
	"PGML.pl",
	"parserPopUp.pl",
	"parserMultiAnswer.pl",
	"parserRadioButtons.pl",
	#"source.pl",        # allows code to be displayed on certain sites.
	#"PGcourse.pl", 	 # Customization file for the course
   	);

TEXT(beginproblem());

##############################################################
#
#  Setup
#
#

Context("Numeric");
#given
$KV=random(1,10,1);# [m/s^2]
$theta= random(30,60,1);# [-]
$time=random(1,10,1); #[s]

#computation
$Ans = (3/8*$KV*($time**2)*(0.01**2)*1/(tan($theta*pi/180))**2)**(1/3);

#set tolerance
Context()->flags->set(
tolerance=>.05,);

##############################################################
#
#  PGML 
#
#

BEGIN_PGML

[@ image("UBC-FLU-18-049.png", width=>[$width], height=>[$height]) @]*

As shown in the diagram, water enters the bottom of the cone at [`V=Kt`], with average velocity uniformly increasing. Assuming [`h=0`] at [`t=0`], if [`d`] is very small, what is the water surface rise [`h(t)`] at [`t=[$time]`] [`s`]? Use [`K=[$KV]`] [`m/s^2`], [`d=0.01`] [`m`], [`\theta=[$theta]`].

[`h([$time])=`] [____]{"$Ans"} [`m`]

END_PGML

